{{Campaignbox Reconquista}}
The '''Crusade of Barbastro''' (also known as the '''Siege of Barbastro''' or '''War of Barbastro''') was an international expedition, sanctioned by [[Pope Alexander II]], to take the [[Spain|Spanish]] city of [[Barbastro]], then part of the [[Banu Hud|Hudid]] [[Taifa of Lérida|Emirate of Lārida]].{{Sfn|Lapeña Paul|2004|p=159}} A large army composed of elements from all over [[Western Europe]] took part in the siege and conquest of the city (1064). The nature of the expedition, famously described by [[Ramón Menéndez Pidal]] as "a crusade before the crusades",{{sfn|Sarrió Cucarella|2012}} is discussed in historiography, and the [[Crusade|crusading]] element of the campaign is still a moot point.{{Sfnm|Ayala Martínez|2011|1p=104|Rodríguez García|2000|2pp=357-358}}

==Expedition==
Pope Alexander II first preached the Reconquista in 1063 as a "Christian emergency."{{sfn|Bishko|1932|p=62}} It was also preached in [[Burgundy (region)|Burgundy]], probably with the permission or participation of [[Hugh of Cluny]], where the abbot's brother, [[Thomas de Chalon]], led the army.{{sfn|Bishko|1932|p=62}} Certainly zeal for the crusade spread elsewhere in [[France]], for [[Amatus of Montecassino]] notes that the "grand chivalry of the French and Burgundians and other peoples" (''grant chevalerie de Francoiz et de Borguegnons et d'autre gent'') was present at the siege.{{sfn|Bishko|1932|p=62}} Thus, a large army, primarily of Frenchmen and Burgundians; along with a papal contingent, made up mostly of [[Italo-Normans]], as well as a local [[Reconquista|Spanish army]] made up of [[Catalan counties|Catalans]] and [[Kingdom of Aragon|Aragonese]]; was present at the siege when it began in 1064. Later, these [[Catalan counties|Catalan]] and [[Kingdom of Aragon|Aragonese]] soldiers would be disgusted by the infamous crimes committed by those [[Italo-Normans|Normans]] after the capture of the city.<ref>{{cite book|author= Calderón Ortega, José Manuel|title= Los desastres de la guerra: reflexiones sobre la muerte de prisioneros y cautivos durante la Edad Media|url= http://revistas.uned.es/index.php/ETFIII/article/view/1636/1517|page= 34}}</ref> The leader of the papal contingent was a Norman by the name of [[William of Montreuil]].{{sfn|O'Callaghan|1983|p=197}} The leader of the Spaniards was [[Sancho Ramírez, King of Aragón and Navarre|Sancho Ramírez]], [[King of Aragon]], whose realm was greatly threatened by the Moors to the south. The largest component, the [[Aquitainian]], was led by the [[Duke of Aquitaine|Duke]] [[William VIII of Aquitaine|Guy-Geoffrey]], to whom one historian calls the "Christian generalissimo".{{sfn|Bishko|1932|p=62}} Though the makeup of this grand army has been subject to much dispute, that it contained a large force of Frankish knights is generally agreed upon.{{sfn|O'Callaghan|1983|p=197}}

The duke of Aquitaine led the army through the [[Pyrenees]] at [[Somport]]. He joined the Catalan army at [[Girona]] early in 1064. The entire army then marched past [[Graus]], which had resisted assault twice before, and moved against Barbastro, then part of the [[taifa]] of [[Lleida]] ruled by [[Al-Muzaffar of Lleida|Al-Muzaffar]].{{sfn|Bishko|1932|p=62}} The city was besieged for forty days until it surrendered according to both Muslim and Christian sources.{{sfn|Marín-Guzmán|1992|p=299}}

Aside from [[William of Montreuil]] and [[William VIII of Aquitaine|Guy-Geoffrey]], a 1078 story about the [[Normans]] would place [[Robert Crispin]] as the leader of the campaign.{{Sfn|Lapeña Paul|2004|p=160}}

==Consequences==
Terms were given by the Christians to spare the lives of the Muslims and respect their properties, but the pact was quickly broken.{{sfn|Marín-Guzmán|1992|p=299}} Another source tells that the garrison offered to surrender their property and property of their families in exchange for letting them leave the town, and so it was agreed with the besiegers.{{sfn|Ibn Hayyan|1981}} However, the Crusaders didn't honour the treaty and killed the soldiers as they came out. Crusade soldiers plundered and sacked the city without mercy.{{sfn|Marín-Guzmán|1992|p=299}} It is said fifty thousand Muslims were killed or captured and the victors divided an enormous amount of booty.{{sfn|Chaytor|1933|p=37}} The contemporary Muslim chronicles suggest the invading forces might have slayed the adult males and enslaved women and children; the numbers however are greatly exaggerated: Barbastro would hardly reach a population of two thousand in those times.{{Sfn|Ubieto Arteta|1981|p=61}}

The [[Al-Andalus|Andalusi]] [[Islam|Muslim]] jurist [[Ibn 'Abd al-Barr]], among the witnesses of the fall of Barbastro, described the aftermath as follows:

<blockquote>''"What can be your opinion, Oh Muslims, when you see [[Mosque|masajid]] and oratories, that once were witness to the recitation of the [[Quran|Qur’ān]] and the sweetness of the call to prayer; immersed in [[polytheism|širk]] and slander, loaded with bells and crosses, in the place of the followers of [[Rahman (name)|ar-Raḥmān]]: [[Imam|aʼimmah]] and pious men, vergers and [[Muezzin|muʾaḏḏinūn]]...are dragged away by the [[Kafir|kuffār]] like animals for sacrifice, they are brought to the butcher; they prostrate themselves humbly in the [[Mosque|masajid]] which are then burnt and reduced to ashes while the [[Kafir|kuffār]] laugh and insult us, and our [[Dīn]] wails and weeps."''{{sfn|Sarrió Cucarella|2012}}</blockquote>

The plight of women seems to have been particularly difficult as a consequence of the siege and victory of the crusaders. Many died during the siege of thirst-related diseases and were subjected to degrading treatment after victory, converting them into servants and sex slaves, or sometimes even exposing them to the torture of their husbands.{{sfn|Ibn Hayyan|1981}}

The crusaders made off with a huge booty. The ''[[Kitab al-Rawd al-Mitar]]'' records the capture of a good many Saracen girls and Saracen treasures.{{sfn|al-Bakri|Harbi al-Himyari|1992}} [[Armengol III of Urgel]], the brother-in-law of King Sancho Ramírez, was entrusted with the government of the city. On 17 April 1065, after roughly ten months of occupation,{{Sfn|Lapeña Paul|2004|p=160}} the Moors easily retook the city and undid all the crusaders' work, massacring the small garrison.{{sfn|Bishko|1932|p=62}} Thibaut, the Burgundian leader, died, possibly of wounds received on campaign, while returning to France after the loss of the city in 1065.{{sfn|Bishko|1932|p=62}}

==Historiography==
Historian [[Reinhart Dozy]] first began a study of the War in the mid-nineteenth century based on the scarce primary sources, mainly Amatus and [[Ibn Hayyan]].{{sfn|Ferreiro|1983}} Dozy first suggested the participation of a papal element based on Ibn Hayyan's reference to the "cavalry of Rome."{{sfn|Ferreiro|1983|p=131}} Subsequent historiography has stressed the [[Cluniac]] element in the War, primarily the result of [[Ferdinand I of León]]'s recent attempts to introduce the [[Cluniac reform]] to Spain and inspired by the death of [[Ramiro I of Aragon]] following the failed [[Siege of Graus]].

This interpretation has been criticized in more recent decades, especially the papal connection and Italian involvement.{{sfn|Ferreiro|1983}} It has been suggested that Alexander was preoccupied with the [[Antipope Cadalus]] at the time and did not preach a [[plenary indulgence]] for warriors of the Reconquista until the 1073 campaign of [[Ebles II of Roucy]]. It has also been theorized that it was not William of Montreuil, but Guy Geoffrey, who was the "Roman" leader implied by Ibn Hayyan.{{sfn|Ferreiro|1983}}

